<p></p>
<p>
The regular dodecahedron, often simply called "the" dodecahedron, is the <a=
 href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PlatonicSolid.html">Platonic solid</=
a> composed of 20 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PolyhedronVertex=
.html">polyhedron
 vertices</a>, 30 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PolyhedronEdge.h=
tml">polyhedron edges</a>, and 12 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
Pentagon.html">pentagonal</a> <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Face=
.html">faces</a>, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/RegularDodecahedron/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"43" height=3D"21" alt=3D"12{=
5}">. It is illustrated above together with a wireframe version
 and a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Net.html">net</a> that can =
be used for its construction.
</p>
<p>
The regular dodecahedron is also the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/UniformPolyhedron.html">uniform polyhedron</a> with Maeder index 23 (Mae=
der 1997), Wenninger index 5 (Wenninger 1989), Coxeter index
 26 (Coxeter <i>et al. </i>1954), and Har'El index 28 (Har'El 1993). It is =
given by
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SchlaefliSymbol.html">Schl=C3=
=A4fli symbol</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/RegularDodecahedron/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"40" height=3D"21" alt=3D"{5,=
3}"> and the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WythoffSymbol.html">W=
ythoff symbol</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/RegularDodecahedron/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"24" alt=3D"3|2=
5">.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"446.368" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/DodecahedronProjections_1000.svg"=
 class=3D"" alt=3D"DodecahedronProjections">
</div>
<p>
A number of symmetric projections of the regular dodecahedron are illustrat=
ed above.
</p>
<p>
The regular dodecahedron is implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfra=
m.com/language/">Wolfram Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wo=
lfram.com/language/ref/Dodecahedron.html">Dodecahedron</a></tt>[]
 or <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/UniformPolyhed=
ron.html">UniformPolyhedron</a></tt>[<tt>"Dodecahedron"</tt>],
 and precomputed properties are available as <tt><a href=3D"http://referenc=
e.wolfram.com/language/ref/PolyhedronData.html">PolyhedronData</a></tt>[<tt=
>"Dodecahedron"</tt>].
</p>
<p>
There are 43380 distinct nets for the regular dodecahedron, the same number=
 as for the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Icosahedron.html">icos=
ahedron</a> (Bouzette and Vandamme, Hippenmeyer
 1979, Buekenhout and Parker 1998). Questions of <a href=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/PolyhedronColoring.html">polyhedron
 coloring</a> of the regular dodecahedron can be addressed using the <a hre=
f=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PolyaEnumerationTheorem.html">P=C3=B3lya
 enumeration theorem</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/gifs/dodeca-o.jpg" class=
=3D"" style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"300" alt=3D"Origam=
i dodecahedron">
</div>
<p>
The image above shows an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Origami.h=
tml">origami</a> regular dodecahedron constructed using six dodecahedron un=
its, each consisting of a single sheet of paper
 (Kasahara and Takahama 1987, pp.&nbsp;86-87).
</p>
<p>
A dodecahedron appears as part of the staircase being ascending by alligato=
r-like lizards in Escher's 1943 lithograph "Reptiles" (Bool <i>et al. </i>1=
982,
 p.&nbsp;284; Forty 2003, Plate 32). Two dodecahedra also appear as polyhed=
ral "stars"
 in M.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Escher's 1948 wood engraving "Stars" (Forty 2003, Plate
 43). The IPV pod that transports Ellie Arroway (Jodi Foster) through a net=
work of
 wormholes in the 1997 film <i><a href=3D"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos=
/ASIN/0790733226/ref=3Dnosim/ericstreasuretro">Contact</a></i>
 was enclosed in a dodecahedral framework.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/gifs/eclipse.jpg" class=3D=
"" style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"269" alt=3D"Charles P=
erry's Eclipse sculpture">
</div>
<p>
A 40-foot high sculpture (Nath 1999) known as <i>Eclipse</i> is displayed i=
n the Hyatt Regency Hotel in San Francisco. It was constructed by Charles P=
erry, and is
 composed of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Reg=
ularDodecahedron/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:1=
00%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"36" height=3D"21" alt=3D"1440">
 pieces of anodized aluminum tubes and assembled over a period of four mont=
hs (Kraeuter
 1999). The layered sculpture begins with a regular dodecahedron, but each =
face then
 rotates outward. At the midpoint of the rotation, it forms an <a href=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/Icosidodecahedron.html">icosidodecahedron</a>.
 Then, as the 12 pentagons continue to rotate outward, it forms a <a href=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SmallRhombicosidodecahedron.html">small
 rhombicosidodecahedron</a>.
</p>
<p>
Dodecahedra were known to the Greeks, and 90 models of dodecahedra with kno=
bbed vertices have been found in a number of archaeological excavations in =
Europe dating from the Gallo-Roman period in locations ranging from militar=
y camps to public bath houses to treasure chests (Schuur).
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"177.774" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/DodecahedralGraph_701.svg" class=
=3D"" alt=3D"DodecahedralGraph">
</div>
<p>
The dodecahedron has the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Icosahedr=
alGroup.html">icosahedral group</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/images/equations/RegularDodecahedron/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula=
" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"14" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"I_h"> of symmetries. The connectivity of
 the vertices is given by the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Dode=
cahedralGraph.html">dodecahedral graph</a>.
 There are three <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DodecahedronStell=
ations.html">dodecahedron stellations</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"912.96" src=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/DodecahedronConvexHulls_1000.svg" =
class=3D"" alt=3D"DodecahedronConvexHulls">
</div>
<p>
The regular dodecahedron is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Co=
nvexHull.html">convex hull</a> of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/Cube5-Compound.html">cube 5-Compound</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/DitrigonalDodecadodecahedron.html">ditrigonal
 dodecadodecahedron</a>, third <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Dod=
ecahedronStellations.html">dodecahedron
 stellation</a> hull, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GreatDitrigo=
nalIcosidodecahedron.html">great ditrigonal
 icosidodecahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GreatRhomb=
icTriacontahedron.html">great rhombic
 triacontahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GreatStellat=
edDodecahedron.html">great stellated dodecahedron</a>,
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RhombicHexecontahedron.html">rhom=
bic hexecontahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SmallDitr=
igonalIcosidodecahedron.html">small
 ditrigonal icosidodecahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/Tetrahedron5-Compound.html">tetrahedron
 5-compound</a>, and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Tetrahedron10=
-Compound.html">tetrahedron 10-compound</a>.
</p>
