<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DualPolyhedron.html">dual poly=
hedron</a> of a dodecahedron with unit edge lengths is an <a href=3D"https:=
//mathworld.wolfram.com/Icosahedron.html">icosahedron</a> with edge lengths
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/RegularDodecahe=
dron/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">,
 where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/RegularDo=
decahedron/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRatio.html">golden r=
atio</a>. As a result, the centers of
 the faces of an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Icosahedron.html"=
>icosahedron</a> form a dodecahedron,
 and vice versa (Steinhaus 1999, pp.&nbsp;199-201).
</p>
